Machine Learning Final ( IMDB Dataset Exploration)¶

Problem Definition¶

Context¶

The main task for the project evolves around doing sentiment analysis on the review dataset. This Natural language Processing problem aims to determine the sentiments and emotions expressed in the review. These emotions can be in form of textual data such as comments reviews or social media posts.

Objective¶

For this project the objective is to perform sentiment analysis on IMDB dataset. This IMDB dataset consists of 50,000 reviews from the internet movie Database. Furthermore, dataset is split into two parts, 25,000 for train and 25,000 for testing. Finally,the dataset is classified into negative and positive reviews.

Goal¶

Now in this project we will work on the negative and postive reviews by building a machine learning model that can accurately classify negative and positive reviews based on the content provided. To explain more about the sentiments, it is understood that positive reviews are supposed to express sense of satisfaction or approval whereas, the negative reviews consist of a critical viewpoint or dissatisfaction. In this project we are going to build a network and examine how the model performs on the given dataset and how it performs on the unseen dataset. Along with that we are going to use multiple techniques to see how we can mitigate the issue of overfitting in models.

Key Components¶

The key components of the project can be calssified into two where one is the input where we provide the model with the input data and the second is the output. The input willl include textual movie reviews and each review is represented as sequence of words. This data is going to be preprocessed to map the words into integer indices. The output for the model is going to be a binary classification that indicates whether the review is positive or negative.

Importance¶

The importance of this project revolves around its application. This can be in multiple domains such as understanding product reviews, customer feedback and user opinions. However, for this project the application will help us to understand movie reviews and how good our model is able to understand the sentiments to explore whether the movie was liked or disliked by people.

Challenges¶

  • Imbalanced Classes: The model must perform well in classifying the sentiments even when the classes are imbalanced.
  • Overfitting/Underfitting: The model must balance the complexity in order to avoid the overfitting where we will see the ability of the model how well it memorizes the data. Similarly, balance the Overfitting where the model fails to capture the data and therefore it effects the results. For IMDB dataset capturing and memorizing would mean understanding the sentiments and the words in a series of words to classify whether its negative or positive.
  • Generalization: Along with working on the IMDB dataset, we must work on making sure that the dataset not only performs well on this dataset but performs good in unseen data as this will be crucial and the project will make sure it eveluates this aspect.

Loading and Preprocessing ( IMDB Dataset )¶

The IMDB datset comes with keras package and the dataset is already preprocessed, which means that the words are converted into integers. This would be a better way to actually process and work on the dataset that is easier for the machine to understand. In the following code we are going to load 10,000 most frequently occuring words into the training dataset and the words that are rare will be ignored. The purpose of doing this is to make the process more efficient by making the data smaller and easier to process.

Vectorization¶

The next major step in creating the model is converting the word indices to binary matrices. The vectorization process is crucial as neural networks cannot take integers as an input and therefore they require numerical input. This process transforms the data into a format that is suitable for the neural network and enables us to feed it to the network. Similarly, another task that we perform here is creating binary matrix representation. Here each row in the matrix corresponds to a review , and the columns represent a word in the vocabulary. For example , the presence of 1 in the matrix would represent presence of a word in the matrix. Now the reason we do this is make the word handling efficient in the presence or absense of reviews as it simplifies the input format.

In [ ]:
import numpy as np

def vectorize_sequences(sequences, dimension=10000):
    results = np.zeros((len(sequences), dimension))        #1
    for i, sequence in enumerate(sequences):
        results[i, sequence] = 1.                          #2
    return results

x_train = vectorize_sequences(train_data)                  #3
x_test = vectorize_sequences(test_data)

Now when we examine the way the samples look below, we can see we can see that we see that the value at each position indicates the presence of word and the 0 for absence of any word in the first training sample.

Now in the code above , these two variables basically contain the sentiment label of the reviews , and that would mean 1's and 0's which means either a positive or negative review. In this code the we convert these labels into numpy arrays which are more versatile for numerical operations. Finally, the integer labels are converted into floating point numbers and this is important as the final layer of the neural network will use the sigmoid activation function which basically expects input labels into floating point format.

Building the Network¶

Now in this part we will build the network now that we have the sequences ready. The input data consists of vectors which are the word sequences and the labels in the data are scalars which means 0's or 1's. Now here we pick our network architecture. This is a stack of fully dense Layers. The architecture consists of two intermeddiate layers, each with 16 hidden units and a third layer for output. The intermediate layers use the Rectified Linear Unit which is also known as relu which is the activation function. Then, the final layer uses a sigmoid activation function that provides us with a probability score between 0 and 1.
Similarly, its important to understand the hidden units. As in each layer these units determine the dimensionality of the representation spaces which in out case is 16. More hidden layers allow the network to process and learn with more complex respresentations, However this comes at a cost of increasing the computational cost. Additionally, the weight matrix for each layer has a shape, which in our case projects the input data into a 16 dimensional space.
Another main aspect of this network is that we are using two main activation functions, which are relu and sigmoid . The relu function is used in the intermediate layers to introduce the non linearity by making the negative values zero. The sigmoid function in the end will provide the probability of the interpretation.

In [ ]:
from keras import models
from keras import layers
In [ ]:
model = models.Sequential()
model.add(layers.Dense(16, activation='relu', input_shape=(10000,)))
model.add(layers.Dense(16, activation='relu'))
model.add(layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))

Choosing the loss function and the Optimiser.¶

Now that we have the output from the last layer the problem here is that the output is the probabilities created formthe sigmoid function which is binary. Now , we need a loss function, To move forward we picked the binary crossentropy function over the other options. The reason we went forward with this function is because this function measures the distance between the probabilty distributions, Now in our case it will basically quantify the difference between the actual distribution values and the ones that are predicted. Additionally, we picked an optimiser RMSprop which is an algorithm which is good at adapting to the learning rates for each of the parameters individually.

In [ ]:
model.compile(optimizer='rmsprop',
              loss='binary_crossentropy',
              metrics=['accuracy'])

Configuring the optimiser¶

This process involves customising the parameters of the optimiser. Which in our case would be adding the learning rate 'lr' of 0.001. This is responsible for allowing fine tuning of this optimisers behaviour.

plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.legend()

Observation¶

In the graph above we can see that the training loss consistently decreases with each epoch, this is exactly what we were expecting in the gradient decent optimization process. On the other side the validation shows an interesting pattern and the change in the line while the loss peaks at some epochs indicates potential overfitting.

Observation¶

In the training and validation accuracy graph, after each epoch we can see that the training accuracy improves. The problem is with the validation accuracy shows a peak in the 4th epoch which may make the model struggle in working with unseen and new data.

Assessing the results¶

In this graph we can clearly see there has been overfitting in the model. This means that the model is optimising more on the model data and therefore this can lead to the model being less generalized. Due to the overfitting issue, we can see that some measures can be taken to reduce overfitting. for instance, by making the training stop after three epochs will prevent the model from learning overly specific patterns.

Retraining the model from scratch¶

As we analyzed above while assessing the results, we saw that there was indication of overfitting in the model. Therefore we move on by training a new network from scratch for only four epochs and then evaluating whether we see any better results. The purpose of this step is to explore wheter stopping the training earlier helps the model to work better with unseen and new data. In the code below we have made some changes to the model. Now a new model is created that uses Sequential model from keras. This will consist two intermediate layers with 16 units. The model is compiled using the same loss function as before. The main change is in the training where we have performed the training for only four epochs with the batch size of 512. The results are stored in the result variable.

Further Exploring the techniques¶

Now we saw in the process above that we created a network, trained the model and assesed the results, we observed that the results shows overfitting adn therefore we came up with a simple solution of reducing epochs and that gave us improvement over the previous results. Now, we can use other techniques and analyze how we can improve the models performance and see if we can increase the accuracy of the model.

Changing the Loss Function and Activation function¶

As we require multiple exploration of the model , its better to create a function that takes the values that we intend to change and then gives us result of the improvement and we can asses the changings in a better way. The main things that we need to change are the loss function, the activation function, the number of epochs and the test accuracy. Now another function that I am going to create is the results function. The purpose of creating this funcion is to store the results from the experiments that we carry out so we can store them. In the end we can use these results for comparison and see how the experiments affected the accuracy and loss of the model.

In [ ]:
# defining a dictionary to store the results 
model_results = []
# function takes the details fo the experiement that 
# is carried out and adds it into the model_results dictionary
def store_results(activate_func,loss_func, 
                  num_ep, net_size,batch_size, 
                  test_loss,test_acc):
    model_results.append({
        'Loss function': loss_func,
        'Activation': activate_func,
        'Epochs': num_ep,
        'Network Size': net_size,
        'Batch Size':  batch_size,
        'Loss': test_loss,
        'Accuracy': test_acc
    })

The function below will take the history object to display the results from the model. Here I have used similar implementation from the code that was used in the report above. Additionally we have added the validation losses values from the original imdb dataset. The purpose of doing this is to compare the resulst while we do experimentation.

def plot_results(history):
    history_dict = history.history
    history_dict.keys()
    loss_values = history_dict['loss']
    val_loss_values = history_dict['val_loss']
    acc_values = history_dict['acc']
    acc_values = history_dict['acc']
    val_acc_values = history_dict['val_acc']
    epochs = range(1, len(acc_values) + 1)
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))

    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)

    plt.plot(epochs, loss_values, 'bo', label='Training loss')                      #1
    plt.plot(epochs, val_loss_values, 'b', label='Validation loss')                 #2
    #  here in the code I have made some modification
    # to limit the array of values to be equal
    #  to the length of the epochs of current model
    # so the plotting does not give any error
    plt.plot(epochs, org_val_loss_values[:len(loss_values)],
             'r', label='Original Validation loss')    #3
    
    plt.title('Training and validation loss')
    plt.xlabel('Epochs')
    plt.ylabel('Loss')
    plt.legend()

    # Plot training and validation accuracy
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    plt.plot(epochs, acc_values, 'bo', label='Training acc')
    plt.plot(epochs, val_acc_values, 'b', label='Validation acc')
    plt.plot(epochs, org_val_acc_values[:len(loss_values)],
             'r', label='Original Validation acc')
    plt.title('Training and Validation accuracy')
    plt.xlabel('Epochs')
    plt.ylabel('Loss')
    plt.legend()

    plt.show()

The function below is the main function that is resposible for building the network and we are going to use the functions that we created above in this function. This function will also be changed and modified for experiments however the functions above will most likely stay the same.

In [ ]:
def train_model_results(act_function,loss_function,
                        num_epochs, net_size, batch):
    x_value = x_train[:10000]
    partial_x_train_val = x_train[10000:]
    y_value = y_train[:10000]
    partial_y_train_value = y_train[10000:]
    model = models.Sequential()
    model.add(layers.Dense(net_size,
                           activation=act_function,
                           input_shape=(10000,)))
    model.add(layers.Dense(net_size, activation=act_function))
    model.add(layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))

    model.compile(optimizer='rmsprop',
                  loss=loss_function, metrics=['acc'])
    history = model.fit(partial_x_train_val, partial_y_train_value,
                        epochs=num_epochs, batch_size=batch,
                        validation_data=(x_value, y_value))
    results = model.evaluate(x_test, y_test)
    #  storing the results in the dictionary 
    store_results(act_function,loss_function,
                  num_epochs, net_size,batch,
                  results[0], results[1])
    # Printing the results along with every model
    print(
        f'Activation Function : {act_function} Loss Function : {loss_function} Number of Epochs: {num_epochs}')
    print(f'Loss Test : {results[0]} Accuracy Test : {results[1]}')
    plot_results(history)

Evaluation¶

By changing batch sizes, we were able to see drastic changes in both limits. By using a lower batch size in the first experiment we saw that tha validation loss increased to a way higher value and it basically got overfit right from the start. However, by using a bigger batch size we were able to see a way lower validation loss. Additionally, a higher batch size also showed a more stable and straighter line. The model got overfit way later as compared to the original model.

Evaluation¶

By comparing the network size modification , we understood that by making the network smaller, which in our case was 4. The validation loss overfits later compare to the original validation loss values. Whereas, when we go to the other extreme by increasing the network size to 512 the model reacts in a loud way. This means that the loss values peak at extreme between 10 and 13 epochs. Along with this we can see that this experiment shows a higher validation loss compared to the original model. higher network size shows unreliable values at some epochs in general and it would be risky to evaluate values at multiple epochs as we might end up getting way higher values. For instance of we use 16 epochs then we might get a validation loss of more than 100 percent.

Now in this part of experimentation , we are going to create two more functions , one for introducing dropout technique that is used to mitigate overfitting and along with that we are going to use Regularization techniques to also see whether they show results in fixing the overfitting issue.

Dropout¶

The dropout technique is another technique to reduce or mitigate overfitting. In this technique we basically drop some features in each iteration. Here this can mean either dropping out or setting the features to zero. This is done to make the network rely less on any single feature. The reason this methos works is that switching off some features makes the network more robust, as it cant rely on any specific feature as it might get dropped. Therefore, in the following code I have created a function that adds dropout lines after every layer.

In [ ]:
def train_model_results_drop(act_function,loss_function,
                             num_epochs, net_size, batch):
    x_value = x_train[:10000]
    partial_x_train_val = x_train[10000:]
    y_value = y_train[:10000]
    partial_y_train_value = y_train[10000:]
    model = models.Sequential()
    model.add(layers.Dense(net_size,
                           activation=act_function,
                           input_shape=(10000,)))
    model.add(layers.Dropout(0.5))
    model.add(layers.Dense(16, activation=act_function))
    model.add(layers.Dropout(0.5))
    model.add(layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))
    model.compile(optimizer='rmsprop',
                  loss=loss_function, metrics=['acc'])
    history_drop = model.fit(partial_x_train_val,
                             partial_y_train_value, epochs=num_epochs,
                             batch_size=batch,
                             validation_data=(x_value, y_value))
    results = model.evaluate(x_test, y_test)
    store_results(act_function,loss_function,
                  num_epochs, net_size,batch,
                  results[0], results[1])

    print(
        f'Activation Function : {act_function}Loss Function : {loss_function} Number of Epochs: {num_epochs}'

Adding L2 Weight Regularization to the model¶

Regularization is one of the popular techniques to mitigate overfitting. In regularization we add penalties for the weights of the network. In L2 regularization specifically, we do this by limiting the weights to not take large values, this ensures even distribution of values.

In [ ]:
from keras import regularizers

def train_model_results_l2(act_function,loss_function,
                           num_epochs, net_size, batch):
    x_value = x_train[:10000]
    partial_x_train_val = x_train[10000:]
    y_value = y_train[:10000]
    partial_y_train_value = y_train[10000:]
    model = models.Sequential()
    model.add(layers.Dense(net_size, kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.001),
                        activation=act_function, input_shape=(10000,)))
    model.add(layers.Dense(net_size, kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.001),
                        activation=act_function))
    model.add(layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))
    model.compile(optimizer='rmsprop', loss=loss_function, metrics=['acc'])
    history_l2 = model.fit(partial_x_train_val, partial_y_train_value,
                           epochs=num_epochs, batch_size=batch,
                           validation_data=(x_value, y_value))
    results = model.evaluate(x_test, y_test)
    store_results(act_function,loss_function,
                  num_epochs, net_size,batch,

Conclusion¶

The project above works extensively on IMDB moviw reviews dataset. The project starts by working on the dataset and getting the dataset ready for using it as an input. Then the project builts a network by picking suitable loss and activation function and builds a network. The project then validates the network by assesing the network for validation loss and accuracy. The project then further works on exploring techniques that are used for reducing overfitting. These techniques include changing hyperparameters and similarly, using techniques like regularization and dropout. Finally the project uses the observation of graphs and the dataset collected to see which combination and techniques affected the accuracy and precision. I was concluded that all techniques were able to get similar accuracy however, the mean_squared error loss function along with relu function provided with the lowest validation loss and highest accuracy.
